Polarization state

How to describe p-state

we use E=E0ei(kz−wt)\boldsymbol{E}=\boldsymbol{E_0}e^{i(kz-wt)}E=E0​ei(kz−wt) to describe the state of the light. Usually, we choose a certain location. It is doesn't matter, however the easiest one is z=0. So we let z=0 and E=E0e−iwt\boldsymbol{E}=\boldsymbol{E_0}e^{-iwt}E=E0​e−iwt. However E\boldsymbol{E}E can still change when time changes. So how E0eiwt\boldsymbol{E_0}e^{iwt}E0​eiwt changes with time is called polarization state.

So we can choose horizontal base H^\hat{\boldsymbol{H}}H^ and vertical base V^\hat{\boldsymbol{V}}V^. However there is a question: suppose that light comes towards you and you see it is right-hand, but if looking in the other way, it is left-hand. So we keep k\boldsymbol{k}k towards you.

And now we have the vector E0\boldsymbol{E_0}E0​, and E0=EHH^+EVV^\boldsymbol{E_0}=E_H \boldsymbol{\hat{H}}+E_V\boldsymbol{ \hat{V}}E0​=EH​H^+EV​V^. If the component of E\boldsymbol{E}E is real, we can let:

EH=AEV=BE_H=A\\ E_V=BEH​=AEV​=B

and then the whole vector was determined. And E\boldsymbol{E}E can only oscillate along the diraction. However the two component may have a phase relation, such as, E\boldsymbol{E}E can rotate. So EH,EVE_H, E_VEH​,EV​ should be complex:

EH=AeiϕHEV=BeiϕVE_H=Ae^{i\phi_H}\\ E_V=Be^{i\phi _V}EH​=AeiϕH​EV​=BeiϕV​

Fix A,B,ϕH,ϕVA,B,\phi _H,\phi _VA,B,ϕH​,ϕV​, and the polarization state can be fixed. However actually the relative phase matters. And we can write E\boldsymbol{E}E as:

E=AeiϕHH^+BeiϕVV^e−iwt=eiϕH(AH^+BeiϕV^)e−iwt(ϕ=ϕV−ϕH)\begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{E}=&Ae^{i\phi _H}\boldsymbol{\hat{H}}+Be^{i\phi _V}\boldsymbol{\hat{V}}e^{-iwt}\\ =&e^{i\phi _H}(A \hat{\boldsymbol{H}}+Be^{i\phi}\boldsymbol{\hat{V}})e^{-iwt}\\ &\small(\phi =\phi _V-\phi _H) \end{aligned}E==​AeiϕH​H^+BeiϕV​V^e−iwteiϕH​(AH^+BeiϕV^)e−iwt(ϕ=ϕV​−ϕH​)​

why writing the vec that way is because we will write it in a column vec, called Jone's vec:

E0=[ABeiϕ]\boldsymbol{E_0}=\begin{bmatrix} A \\ Be^{i\phi } \\ \end{bmatrix}E0​=[ABeiϕ​]

where:
AAA: amplitude of H component.
BBB: amplitude of V component. A,B>0A,B>0A,B>0.
ϕ=ϕV−ϕH\phi=\phi _V-\phi _Hϕ=ϕV​−ϕH​: phase diff between vertical and horizontal oscillation.

Now we can treat polarization as two orthogonal oscillators. Choose diff A,BA,BA,B and ϕ\phiϕ and you can determine polarization states.

Different p-states

Linear polarized light

ϕ=0 or ϕ=π\phi =0 \text{ or }\phi =\piϕ=0 or ϕ=π. Analysis:

  • ϕ=0,E=[AB]e−iwt\phi =0, \boldsymbol{E}=\begin{bmatrix}A \\B \\\end{bmatrix}e^{-iwt}ϕ=0,E=[AB​]e−iwt . Take the real part: {EH=Acos⁡wtEV=Bcos⁡wttan⁡θ=BA\begin{cases}E_H=A\cos wt\\E_V=B\cos wt\\\tan\theta =\frac{B}{A}\end{cases}⎩⎨⎧​EH​=AcoswtEV​=Bcoswttanθ=AB​​.
  • ϕ=π,E=[A−B]e−iwt\phi =\pi ,\boldsymbol{E}=\begin{bmatrix}A \\-B \\\end{bmatrix}e^{-iwt}ϕ=π,E=[A−B​]e−iwt. Similarly.

Circular polarized light

How to define lead or lag physically?

A=B,ϕ=∓π2A=B,\phi =\mp \frac{\pi }{2}A=B,ϕ=∓2π​. Analysis:

  • ϕ=−π2,E=A[1e−iπ2]e−iwt\phi =-\frac{\pi }{2}, \boldsymbol{E}=A\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ e^{-i \frac{\pi }{2}} \\ \end{bmatrix}e^{-iwt}ϕ=−2π​,E=A[1e−i2π​​]e−iwt.
    The real part is {EH=Acos⁡wtEV=Acos⁡(wt+π2)\begin{cases} E_H=A\cos wt\\ E_V=A\cos (wt+\frac{\pi}{2}) \end{cases}{EH​=AcoswtEV​=Acos(wt+2π​)​
    If t=Δt>0t=\Delta t>0t=Δt>0,EHE_HEH​ will go down from A, and EVE_VEV​ will go minus from 0.
    That means it is C.W rotation, or right-circular polarized light(R,↻\circlearrowright↻).

Now we consider which component is leading in phase, or goes ahead. Remember that ϕ∈(−π,π)\phi \in(-\pi ,\pi )ϕ∈(−π,π). And if ϕ>0\phi >0ϕ>0, EVE_VEV​ is lagging . If ϕ<0\phi <0ϕ<0, EVE_VEV​ is leading. So when ϕ=−π2\phi =\frac{-\pi }{2}ϕ=2−π​, EVE_VEV​ leads EHE_HEH​, and you get R light.

  • ϕ=π2,E=A[1eiπ2]e−iwt\phi= \frac{\pi}{2}, \boldsymbol{E}=A\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ e^{i \frac{\pi }{2}} \\ \end{bmatrix}e^{-iwt}ϕ=2π​,E=A[1ei2π​​]e−iwt.
    That means E\boldsymbol{E}E goes C.C.W, and you will get left-circular polarized light(L, ↺\circlearrowleft↺)

Elliptical polarized light

if putting any A,B,ϕA,B,\phiA,B,ϕ in it, you will get elliptical P-light.

Any A,B,ϕA,B,\phiA,B,ϕ except those above.

E=[ABeiϕ]\boldsymbol{E}=\begin{bmatrix} A \\ Be^{i\phi } \\ \end{bmatrix}E=[ABeiϕ​], and the real part is : {EH=Acos⁡(wt)EV=Bcos⁡(wt−ϕ)\begin{cases} E_H=A\cos(wt)\\ E_V=B\cos(wt-\phi ) \end{cases}{EH​=Acos(wt)EV​=Bcos(wt−ϕ)​. We can draw the picture just like before.

▶Ex.1\color{teal}{\bf{▶ Ex. 1}}▶Ex.1 E0=[2ei(−23π)]\boldsymbol{E_0}=\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ e^{i(-\frac{2}{3}\pi )} \\ \end{bmatrix}E0​=[2ei(−32​π)​]

We can define the amplitude and draw a 2×12\times 12×1 box. From ϕ=−23π\phi =-\frac{2}{3}\piϕ=−32​π, we know how it rotates(↻\circlearrowright↻,because ϕ<0\phi <0ϕ<0 and EVE_VEV​ is leading) and the long-axis diraction(↘\searrow↘, because ∣ϕ∣>π2|\phi |>\frac{\pi}{2}∣ϕ∣>2π​). Also you can know θ\thetaθ in the figure, but you should prove in your hw.

So the take-home message is:

  • A,B,ϕA,B,\phiA,B,ϕ completely define p-state
  • specific condition: linear of circular p-lignt
  • more general: elliptical
  • Jone's vector(and later we will write E\boldsymbol{E}E as ∣E⟩|E\rangle∣E⟩)

Unpolarized light

Those A,B,ϕA,B,\phiA,B,ϕ above are all fixed, that means the phase and amplitude don not change. That is called p-state, or pure state.
In real life, the light is actually not polarized light. So that is the question: how to prepare pure polarized light. Before that, we will talk about unpolarized light(or mixed state in quantum).

As the figure shows, every diraction is possible and there is no phas relations bet two directions. If it is completely random, it is called natural light. It is not easy to express in math, maybe using density matrix. Here we try to use the vector.

Suppose horizontal and vertical component has equal amount. That means :

E=AH^+AeiΔV^,Δ is random\boldsymbol{E}=A \hat{\boldsymbol{H}}+Ae^{i\Delta} \boldsymbol{\hat{V}},\qquad\small\Delta \text{ is random}E=AH^+AeiΔV^,Δ is random

That means Δ\DeltaΔ can jump, or the phase diff bet H^{\boldsymbol{\hat{H}}}H^ direction and V^\hat{\boldsymbol{V}}V^ is random (fixed: polarized state). And when you take average, that term just gone.

Partial polarized

That is the more general case. Even there is no relationship bet diff direction, some wavetrains are more likely to oscillate along a specific direction. In the graph, vertical direction is more likely than horizontal direction:

E=AH^+BeiΔV^,B>A,Δ is random\boldsymbol{E}=A \hat{\boldsymbol{H}}+Be^{i\Delta} \hat{\boldsymbol{V}}, \quad B>A, \Delta\text{ is random}E=AH^+BeiΔV^,B>A,Δ is random

why say it is partial polarized? Because it can be treated as a certain linear p-light plus natural light.

Dirac notation

Now we have a new exp: Dirac notation. Here is a Dirac ket ∣E⟩|E\rangle∣E⟩:

E→∣E⟩=[ABeiϕ](H−V)\boldsymbol{E}\rightarrow|E\rangle= \begin{bmatrix} A \\ Be^{i\phi } \\ \end{bmatrix}_{(H-V)}E→∣E⟩=[ABeiϕ​](H−V)​

Of course this exp is under H-V base, and needless to always say where it is. Here H-V is default base.

And we know:

∣E∣2=E∗⋅E=A2+B2(∝I)|\boldsymbol{E}|^2=\boldsymbol{E}^*\cdot \boldsymbol{E}=A^2+B^2(\propto I)∣E∣2=E∗⋅E=A2+B2(∝I)

How to express that? In linear algebra we use transpose and complex conjugation (because E\boldsymbol{E}E is complex) to exp that. In dirac notation, it is a Dirac bra vector ⟨E∣\langle E|⟨E∣:

E∗⟶adjoint∣E⟩†→⟨E∣=[ABe−iϕ]\boldsymbol{E}^*\overset{\text{adjoint}}{\longrightarrow}|E\rangle^\dagger\rightarrow\langle E|=\begin{bmatrix} A & Be^{-i\phi } \\ \end{bmatrix}E∗⟶adjoint​∣E⟩†→⟨E∣=[A​Be−iϕ​]

So you can write the module as:

∣E∣2=⟨E∣E⟩=A2+B2bra c ket\begin{matrix} |\boldsymbol{E}|^2= & \langle E|E\rangle&= A^2+B^2 \\ & \text{bra c ket}& \\ \end{matrix}∣E∣2=​⟨E∣E⟩bra c ket​=A2+B2​

and

B∗⋅A=∑bi∗ai=⟨B∣A⟩\boldsymbol{B}^*\cdot \boldsymbol{A}=\sum b_i^*a_i=\langle B|A\rangleB∗⋅A=∑bi∗​ai​=⟨B∣A⟩

There is something you need to pay attention to:

  1. The order of Dirac notation matters.
    If you write ⟨A∣B⟩\langle A|B\rangle⟨A∣B⟩, it will give you a number. And if you write ∣A⟩⟨B∣|A\rangle\langle B|∣A⟩⟨B∣,it will give you a matrix.
    So it is "bra ket", not "ket bra"(which we call projector).
  2. Taking conjugate (conjugate in physics=conjugate and transpose) is switch.
    That means: bra→ket; ket→bra. And changer order.
    ▶Pf.\color{green}{\bf{▶ Pf.}}▶Pf. ⟨A∣B⟩=A∗⋅B=∑ai∗bi=(∑bi∗ai)∗=(B∗⋅A)∗=(⟨B∣A⟩)†\langle A|B\rangle=\boldsymbol{A}^*\cdot \boldsymbol{B}=\sum a_i^*b_i=(\sum b_i^*a_i)^*=(\boldsymbol{B}^*\cdot \boldsymbol{A})^*=(\langle B|A\rangle)^\dagger⟨A∣B⟩=A∗⋅B=∑ai∗​bi​=(∑bi∗​ai​)∗=(B∗⋅A)∗=(⟨B∣A⟩)†
    or you can derive from: (AB)†=B†A†(\boldsymbol{A}\boldsymbol{B})^\dagger=\boldsymbol{B}^\dagger \boldsymbol{A}^\dagger(AB)†=B†A†, so (⟨B∣A⟩)†=∣A⟩†⟨B∣†=⟨A∣B⟩(\langle B|A\rangle)^\dagger=|A\rangle^\dagger\langle B|^\dagger=\langle A|B\rangle(⟨B∣A⟩)†=∣A⟩†⟨B∣†=⟨A∣B⟩
    ▶Ex.\color{teal}{\bf{▶ Ex. }}▶Ex. (⟨A∣B⟩∣B⟩)†=⟨B∣⟨A∣B⟩(\langle A|B\rangle|B\rangle)^\dagger=\langle B|\langle A|B\rangle(⟨A∣B⟩∣B⟩)†=⟨B∣⟨A∣B⟩

Preparation of polarization state

Now we have natural light. We firstly need to prepare polarized light. That is the initial condition, and we will do it similarly in quantum.

That is easy by using linear polarizer. Light can only pass along a specific direction and another direction will be absorbed. Or you can use Brewster angle, that means using reflection. You incident the light in the specific angle, and the output will be polarized. And later we will use birefringence crystal.

Malus law

Suppose you have a linear p-light. How will you test it? You can put another polarizer and check the output. If the angle bet A and T-axis is θ\thetaθ, then:
I=I0cos⁡2θI=I_0\cos^2\thetaI=I0​cos2θ

That is called Malus law. It is a natural idea, because Acos⁡θA\cos\thetaAcosθ pass and Asin⁡θA \sin\thetaAsinθ is blocked. So if you rotate the polarizer, you will find intensity changes, from 0 (θ=π2\theta =\frac{\pi}{2}θ=2π​) to I0I_0I0​(θ=0\theta =0θ=0).

In the figure, the first polarizer is called polarizer, and the second is called detector. It is easy to produce and detect linear p-light.

  • circular p-light and natural light

And how about circular p-light passing the linear polarizer? Just consider its H and V component:

polarizer: 起偏器
detector : 检偏器

A[1i]⟶A[10]2A⟶A\qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \begin{aligned} A\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ i \\ \end{bmatrix}&\longrightarrow A\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ \end{bmatrix}\\ \sqrt{2}A&\longrightarrow A \end{aligned}A[1i​]2​A​⟶A[10​]⟶A​

So you can see that

Iout=A2=12IinI_{out}=A^2=\frac{1}{2}I_{in}Iout​=A2=21​Iin​

And how about natural light? You can do the similar thing:

It is such a good work that you even don't need to do integration.

A[1eiΔ]⟶A[10]\qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad A\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ e^{i\Delta} \\ \end{bmatrix}\longrightarrow A\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ \end{bmatrix}A[1eiΔ​]⟶A[10​]

So you will also get:

Iout=12IinI_{out}=\frac{1}{2}I_{in}Iout​=21​Iin​

So you can not tell the diff bet circular p-light and natural light, even if you rotate your polarizer. So the linear polarizer can only detect linear p-light.

  • elliptical p-light and partial p-light

For elliptical p-lignt and partial p-lignt? That is the general condition:

∣E⟩in=[ABeiϕ]|E\rangle_{in}=\begin{bmatrix} A \\ Be^{i\phi } \\ \end{bmatrix}∣E⟩in​=[ABeiϕ​]

you put the T-axis at θ\thetaθ position, and do the calculation. Just let H and V component be projected to T-axis:

ET=Acos⁡θ+Beiϕsin⁡θE_T=A\cos\theta +Be^{i\phi }\sin\thetaET​=Acosθ+Beiϕsinθ

remember they are all complex number and have a phase diff. So

IT=∣ET∣2=A2cos⁡2θ+B2sin⁡2θ+2ABcos⁡θsin⁡θcos⁡ϕI_T=|E_T|^2=A^2\cos^2\theta +B^2\sin^2\theta +2AB\cos\theta \sin\theta \cos\phiIT​=∣ET​∣2=A2cos2θ+B2sin2θ+2ABcosθsinθcosϕ

and it dep on ϕ\phiϕ. Change θ\thetaθ and ITI_TIT​ will change. And the long-axis direction is the biggest ITI_TIT​ direction.

Prepare any p-state

Now we have linear p-light. What we want is to prepare any p-state [ABeiϕ]\begin{bmatrix} A \\ Be^{i\phi } \\ \end{bmatrix}[ABeiϕ​]. We should fix A,BA,BA,B and ϕ\phiϕ.

A theoretical method is, give me horizontal p-light, and vertical p-light, and then add them up with stable phase diff. You can use PBS and interferometer. Light incident PBS (polarization beam spliter) by Brewster angle with the thin film. One beam get vertical-polarized, and the other get horizontal-polarized. We do have this device.

And then we can get p p-light(parallel) and s p-light(perpendicular, German). Use mirrors to get them meet and put another PBS tho combine them. Now we successfully make one overlap the other. Just adjust the mirror and you can change ϕ\phiϕ.

This is too complex because you should adjust the mirrors accurately. But it give me some ideas. That is, make OPL diff ΔL\Delta LΔL to change ϕ=kΔL\phi =k\Delta Lϕ=kΔL.

Linear birefringence in the crystal

Using birefringence crystal is a better way to prepare p-light. Here we just talk about linear birefringence (there is also circular birefringence, called optical activity).

anisotropic: 各向异性

It is related with light propagating in crystal. That is because crystal is anisotropic. Crystal has some particular inside structure.

If you shine in the light normally, you can find the light splits into two beam. One of that goes normally and follows geometric path, called ooo light(ordinary). And the other beam will goes at a certain angle, which disobeys Snell's law. That beam is called eee light(extraordinary).

It is easy to understand in physics (not in math, which is complex). If the polarization is along the dipole, it can make the molecule oscillate, which means give it some energy. That is strong interaction. And it appears the velocity of light decreases and media has index. When they are perpendicular, the inter is very weak(almost can be neglect).

Strong interaction means big index. If there is no inter, index =1 and v has no change.

In isotropic media, the direction of molecules is random. There is equal number of molucules of all the direction. So averagely, the inter of all direction of p-light is same.

However in anisotropic media, it will change. Let's "crystalize" it. You just put all the dipoles along the direction (showing in the figure). Then you can find npn_pnp​ can change with θ\thetaθ. But nsn_sns​ doesn't change. So here s light is ooo light (just here, not all condition)

week6 class2

Which polarization is o,e?

We can see that there is a specific direction(green direction in the figure) in the crystal, along which ooo-light and eee-light has no diff, or ne=non_e=n_one​=no​. That special direction is called optical axis(O.A.). Not all crystal has optical axis, but we don't care that. Optical axis is just a direction, so you can draw many lines in the crystal(shown in the figure).

Now let the light shine in the crystal. Usually k\boldsymbol{k}k and O.A. can form a plain, called principal plain. It is easy to find that ooo-light is perpendicular to principal plain and eee-light is in the plain.

principal plain: 主平面

Next, we will talk about the index.

index (nnn) for the ooo and eee light

Wave-plate (▶Ex.2\color{teal}{\bf{▶ Ex. 2}}▶Ex.2 above)

Quarter (λ4\frac{\lambda}{4}4λ​) wave-plate (Q)

It means (ne−n0)d=λ4+mλ(n_e-n_0)d=\frac{\lambda}{4}+m\lambda(ne​−n0​)d=4λ​+mλ. We don't need to let the thickness of Q be λ4\frac{\lambda}{4}4λ​, because mλm\lambdamλ doesn't matter (+2mπ+2m\pi+2mπ).

Q can change p-state. It can make:

δeo=±π2+2mπ\delta_{eo}=\pm\frac{\pi}{2}+2m\piδeo​=±2π​+2mπ

±\pm± is because we haven't point out the crystal is positive or negative. If we use positive, it is +π2+\frac{\pi}{2}+2π​. And negative crystal leads to −π2-\frac{\pi}{2}−2π​.

However, what is the meaning of δeo=π2\delta_{eo}=\frac{\pi}{2}δeo​=2π​ in positive crystal? That means eee-light lags ooo-light by π2\frac{\pi}{2}2π​. That is because ne>n0n_e>n_0ne​>n0​, which shows ve<vov_e<v_ove​<vo​ and ooo-light travels faster. Ususally we call o-direction fast axis in this case. In negative crystal, e-direction is fast axis.

Summary:
π2\quad\frac{\pi}{2}2π​: eee lags ooo by π2\frac{\pi}{2}2π​;
−π2-\frac{\pi}{2}−2π​: eee leads ooo by π2\frac{\pi}{2}2π​

Why ooo-light leads eee-light in that case? We should talk about its definition:
Let phase ϕ=kz−ωt+ϕ0=kz−ω(t+t0)\phi=kz-\omega t+\phi_0=kz-\omega(t+t_0)ϕ=kz−ωt+ϕ0​=kz−ω(t+t0​). Usually we consider z=0z=0z=0 and the same ttt, and let ϕ=−ωt0∈[−π,π]\phi=-\omega t_0\in [-\pi,\pi]ϕ=−ωt0​∈[−π,π]. And I think that −ω-\omega−ω determines that. Here angular freq is −ω-\omega−ω and if ωt=−ϕ0\omega t=-\phi_0ωt=−ϕ0​ bigger, the phase will lead.
There is a big problem!!!!! I haven't understand that!

Actually, in real application, we ususally don't care which direcion is ooo or e. We just care which is the fast axis.

Now, let's talk about how it changes the p-state.

Analysis of Q-plate

Let

∣Ein⟩=[ABeiϕoe]|E_{in}\rangle=\begin{bmatrix} A \quad\\ Be^{i\phi_{oe}} \\ \end{bmatrix}∣Ein​⟩=[ABeiϕoe​​]

∣Eout⟩=[ABei(ϕoe−δeo)]|E_{out}\rangle=\begin{bmatrix} A \\ Be^{i(\phi_{oe}-\delta_{eo})} \\ \end{bmatrix}∣Eout​⟩=[ABei(ϕoe​−δeo​)​]

▶Ex.2\color{teal}{\bf{▶ Ex. 2}}▶Ex.2 let ∣R⟩|R\rangle∣R⟩ become ∣Ein⟩|E_{in}\rangle∣Ein​⟩. That means ooo leads eee by π2\frac{\pi}{2}2π​. After it pass Q-plate, ooo will leads by π\piπ, and the output will be linear:

Now that is the question: after reflected by the mirror, what is its p-state?

Remember you always look into direction of the light! And now you should set another coordinate: k′=−k\boldsymbol{k}'=-\boldsymbol{k}k′=−k.

So easy to imagine that it will become LLL light. The direction of rotation doesn't change, but your point of view changes.

Now let it pass Q-plate again. Be careful! Because direction of eee also changes! It is now e′=−e\boldsymbol{e}' =-\boldsymbol{e}e′=−e. For LLL light, ooo lags eee in π2\frac{\pi}{2}2π​. After passing Q-plate, phase diff will change into 0 and it will become linear.

However, always remember that the direction of axis has changed. So the direction of oscillation has rotated 90∘\bf90^\circ90∘ from initial polarized light.

So now, by inserting polarizer and waveplate and adjusting the angle, we can create all kinds of p-light.

Half-walf plate(λ2\frac{\lambda}{2}2λ​ plate; H)

H-plate means δeo=(ne−n0)d=λ2\delta_{eo}=(n_e-n_0)d =\frac{\lambda}{2}δeo​=(ne​−n0​)d=2λ​. Its phase diff is ±π\pm \pi±π. Of course they are same. For input light:

∣in⟩=[ABeiϕoe]|in\rangle=\begin{bmatrix} A \\ Be^{i\phi_{oe}} \\ \end{bmatrix}∣in⟩=[ABeiϕoe​​]

The output will be:

∣out⟩=[ABei(ϕoe+π)]=[A−Beiϕoe]|out\rangle=\begin{bmatrix} A \\ Be^{i(\phi_{oe}+\pi)} \\ \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} A \\ -Be^{i\phi_{oe}} \\ \end{bmatrix}∣out⟩=[ABei(ϕoe​+π)​]=[A−Beiϕoe​​]

So just flip ooo (actually VVV) direction.

The take-home message is, H plate doesn't change p-state, just changes the direction.

Create any desired p-state

Now we can create any p-state conveniently. Here we arbitrarily draw a p-stete. Consider a more general condition, that is initially, we have natural light.

Step.1 create pure state, i.e. linear p-state.

Step.2 let it pass a Q-plate. Put fast axis at the spectific direction, and you will get a similar ellipse to the target.

Step.3 put a H-plate bet your ellipse and target, and then your p-state will overlap on the target p-state. Bingo!

Test any input p-state

It is easy to test linear p-state. You can just use linear polarizer. But you can not tell the diff bet natural and circular, or elliptical and partial. However, if you have Q-plate, you can distinguish them.

Now we give an example.

▶Ex.1\color{teal}{\bf{▶ Ex. 1}}▶Ex.1 distinguish elliptical and partial p-light.

Firstly you can use linear polarizer and rotate it. From that you can detect the max and min axis of the elliptical (or the partial).
And then, you can put fast axis of Q-plate along max axis. If it is partial, the output is still partial because you can not change randomness. However, if it is elliptical, it will change into linear! Then you can use a linear polarizer to detect them, and there will be a direction where there is no light. From this, you can distinguish them.

After that, you can prepare and detect all kinds of p-state.

How about expression of optical elements that changes state?

An optical element can change state. Generally speaking, it is a matrix:

O~∣Ein⟩=∣Eout⟩\widetilde{O}|E_{in}\rangle=|E_{out}\rangleO∣Ein​⟩=∣Eout​⟩

O~\widetilde{O}O is Operator, which represents action by optical elements.

Find matrix of Opreator (matrix form in certain base)

Here we start from a simple exp: reflection. We want to know:

[EprEsr]=?[EpiEsi]\begin{bmatrix} E_{pr} \\ E_{s r} \\ \end{bmatrix}=?\begin{bmatrix} E_{p i} \\ E_{si} \\ \end{bmatrix}[Epr​Esr​​]=?[Epi​Esi​​]

Here the direction of pip_ipi​ and prp_{r}pr​ is different. That is because ki=−kr\boldsymbol{k}_{i}=-\boldsymbol{k}_{r}ki​=−kr​ and we set the base according to that. And from book, we know:

rp=EprEpi=n1−n2n1+n2rs=EsrEsi=n2−n1n2+n1\begin{aligned} r_{p}&=\frac{E_{pr}}{E_{p i}}=\frac{n_1-n_2}{n_1+n_2}\\ r_{s}&=\frac{E_{s r}}{E_{si}}=\frac{n_2-n_1}{n_2+n_1} \end{aligned}rp​rs​​=Epi​Epr​​=n1​+n2​n1​−n2​​=Esi​Esr​​=n2​+n1​n2​−n1​​​

Therefore

[EprEsr]=[rpEpirsEsi]=[rp00rs][EpiEsi]=rp[100−1][EpiEsi]\begin{bmatrix} E_{pr} \\ E_{s r} \\ \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} r_pE_{p i} \\ r_sE_{s i} \\ \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix} r_p & 0 \\ 0 & r_s \\ \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} E_{ p i} \\ E_{si} \\ \end{bmatrix}={\color{Red}r_p \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \\ \end{bmatrix}}\begin{bmatrix} E_{p i} \\ E_{si} \\ \end{bmatrix}[Epr​Esr​​]=[rp​Epi​rs​Esi​​]=[rp​0​0rs​​][Epi​Esi​​]=rp​[10​0−1​][Epi​Esi​​]

So that we get reflect matrix:

R~=rp[100−1]\widetilde{R}=r_p \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \\ \end{bmatrix}R=rp​[10​0−1​]

This is the operator that represents reflection. And it is straightforward that if you input L-circular p-light, its output will be R-circular p-light.

Now suppose you have an operator O~\widetilde{O}O(today all O~\widetilde{O}Os are 2x2 matrices). What do you mean that you know O~\widetilde{O}O? That means you know all elements:

REVIEW: Linear algebra

In linear algebra, we can express a linear map fff by a matrix O~\widetilde{O}O in certain base E\boldsymbol{E}E. If E′=EP\boldsymbol{E}'=\boldsymbol{EP}E′=EP
Then

O~E′ base=PTO~E baseP\widetilde{O}_{E'\text{ base}}=\boldsymbol{P}^{T}\widetilde{O}_{E\text{ base}}\boldsymbol{P}OE′ base​=PTOE base​P

Here E,E′\boldsymbol{E},\boldsymbol{E}'E,E′ and P\boldsymbol{P}P are orthogonal matrices. That is indeed the form of similarity transformation.
In that case, P=[∣e1⟩⋯∣en⟩]\boldsymbol{P}=\begin{bmatrix} |e_1\rangle & \cdots & |e_n\rangle \\ \end{bmatrix}P=[∣e1​⟩​⋯​∣en​⟩​], which is the expression in E\boldsymbol{E}E of base vectors in E′\boldsymbol{E'}E′

That is called diagonalization. For a diagonal matrix O~Λ\widetilde{O}_{\Lambda}OΛ​, you can always exp it into:

O~=∑i,jO~Λij∣ei⟩⟨ej∣=∑iλi∣ei⟩⟨ei∣=∑iλiP~ei\widetilde{O}=\sum_{i,j}^{}\widetilde{O}_{\Lambda ij}|e_i\rangle\langle e_j|=\sum_{i}^{}\lambda_i|e_i\rangle\langle e_i|=\sum_{i}^{}\lambda_i \widetilde{P}_{e_i}O=i,j∑​OΛij​∣ei​⟩⟨ej​∣=i∑​λi​∣ei​⟩⟨ei​∣=i∑​λi​Pei​​

That tells you, if you know eigenvalues and eigenvectors, you will know the whole matrix.

Also in linear algebra, we may be more familiar with this forluma:

O~=PO~ΛP†=[∣e1⟩⋯∣en⟩][λ10⋱0λn][⟨e1∣⋮⟨en∣]\widetilde{O}=\boldsymbol{P}\widetilde{O}_{\Lambda}\boldsymbol{P}^\dagger=\begin{bmatrix} |e_1\rangle & \cdots & |e_n\rangle \\ \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1 & & 0 \\ & \ddots & \\ 0 & & \lambda_n \\ \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \langle e_1| \\ \vdots \\ \langle e_n| \\ \end{bmatrix}O=POΛ​P†=[∣e1​⟩​⋯​∣en​⟩​]⎣⎡​λ1​0​⋱​0λn​​⎦⎤​⎣⎡​⟨e1​∣⋮⟨en​∣​⎦⎤​

They are same. We can get the matrix from eigenvalues and eigenvectors through that.
Here P\boldsymbol{P}P is orthogonal matrix and O~Λ\widetilde{O}_{\Lambda}OΛ​ is diagonal matrix. All the diagonal elements of O~Λ\widetilde{O}_{\Lambda}OΛ​ are eigenvalues of O~\widetilde{O}O, i.e. λi\lambda_iλi​.
